commentBody:
@Bob Solo already said this in a reply but it's worth saying again:
The island nation for 25D is definitely endangered by sea-level rise, along with other Pacific islands, the Maldives, and many Alaskan coastal communities. 
May the rest of the world wake up in time!

@SBK in TO

My point is that, even if the clues for the spanners (and everything else) were toughened, I think I'd still solve this easily. 

Stacks make puzzles easier to solve, not harder. Here 135 boxes were mostly filled with very common letters, forming nine recognizable 15-letter entries. How can that be hard to solve?

@Marshall Walthew

I really miss the days of a walk or a single, a stolen base, a bunt up the first base line to advance the runner, and a score on a sac fly.

The worship of the home run has really damaged the game for me.  A home run is exciting for about two seconds.  But watching a runner score from second on a liner to the wall and a play at the plate is enormous fun.  Especially when you're at the ballpark and can watch it all unfold.

@Francis

Ah, yes, words and phrases, making sentences. I get it all 🤣

(I do remember Steve L once explaining sac fly to me though!)

@Anonymous
You bring up an really good point which I had thus far missed: Friday is the one day on which a separate, easier clue list is provided. The "hard" clues should have been, well, harder.

Don't get me wrong, I still thought it an excellent puzzle.

@john ezra
And EWEST would be clued as "most disgusting" and that would trigger a ton of the complaints from the same folks who have disliked semi-invented 'ER' answers?
  Bring it on!

@Andrzej

I didn't leave you any straight lines tonight, I don't think.  My post from last night got taken down.  I'm guessing it would not have had I not pointed it out.

Oh, well, I can't say I'm too surprised. When you play with fire....

@Francis

If you have to go outside, please go to Amazon (or your preferred delivery service) first and order a respirator. Even short term exposure to that outside air cannot be good. An air purifier is also a great suggestion. We keep a couple going year round to help with allergens, and they’re very effective if you remember to change the filters (an ongoing challenge for us). I don’t know about your makeshift setup, but I expect its impact would be very limited. An air purifier can cover an entire room. 

I can’t even imagine how difficult this must be, on top of everything else you and your fellow Minnesotans have been through lately. (HeathieJ, you ok?) You all deserve some good news, and I hope you get it. Soon.

@Francis

We did fans and furnace filters when we faced this, too. We had the bad luck of fires coinciding with a full plumbing replacement, so the garage door had to stay open and they had cut holes in all the walls. The smoke just poured in. I had to call into work that day (wfh) because it was so bad I had to go lay on the downstairs floor to get a much relief as possible. I wore a k95, too.

Wishing you and all the others going through this good health and good spirits.

@Michael
I immediately knew it was: (blank)PANCAKES and tasted it all the way thru solving, yum!  I kept wondering what they call it on menus. Later looked at a favorite restaurant menu, it is called “(name of restaurant)’s cakes”). Google says it translates to green onion pancakes.  

This was a delicious delightful puzzle.

@Down_Home

For obvious reasons I'm not going to go into details.

If the average Parisian heard about it they would probably just shrug.

@Sue S
i'm a mite confused by your question. ;)

I use it often, although I usually say "MITE bit".

@Elle

I can't tell if you're pulling my leg or not 😃

A favorite Polish sweet is "ptasie mleczko", "bird's milk" (or even, bird's little milk). It also was better when it was made with actual bird milk!

@Andrzej

Shoes works too.

We used to put them in other kids' shoes (and were similarly victimized in turn), removed and untended around the campfire.

@Andrzej

I’ve always thought s’mores were vile confections, even as a child.  But then, I’ve never liked marshmallows. I’d take some roasted kielbasa, though.

I, too, found this puzzle extremely daunting at first. But once I decided to flip my usual method and do the Downs first, it became pretty simple. I guess that’s a lesson to me: don’t get caught up in routine!

@Bob
I guess you're still a kid at heart. :)
I didn't mention it in my first post, but I don't like graham crackers, either. I know, I failed being a kid.

@kkseattle

No. I haven't heard of it being a thing in Poland. My wife and I hiked to the top of the Brocken mountain in the German Harz though, which was traditonally considered the foremost meeting spot for witches.

The only pagan-adjacent, night-time celebration over here is Noc Kupały (historically known in Polish as sobótka; Noc Kupały is a loan term from Eastern Slavic languages, of ultimately unknown etymology; Poles are Western Slavs), coinciding with the summer solstice, rooted in pre-Christian, Eastern Slavic tradition. One of its purposes was to scare witches away. I've never taken part in those festivities though (not for any religious reasons, mind you - I guess I just never felt like it).

@Weak
Italics, like bolding or underlining or *asterisking* is a way of intensifying a word; if spoken, "will" would be louder/emphasized.
hope that helps.

@Hugh

Patently and provably false.  The easy ones get routinely and endlessly dumped on here by people like me, except when they also bring a bit of interest or challenge or delight or achievement to the table, as this one so clearly does.

It would be more accurate to say that rarely does everyone love an easy one.

@Petrol
I had CAINE at the end from all the down crossings and then the S at the front, and then from somewhere in all my reading about food and/or watching food shows with Julia Child/Pierre Franey the answer surfaced.
D'oh Holland. Not an unreasonable guess.

@Susan E

Not sure what’s puzzling about Matt’s statement. It’s very clear. Obviously not everyone, but most, especially veterans, would say this is an extremely easy Friday puzzle. It’s a lovely grid and construction, no doubt, but when you have so many easy crosses it absolutely decreases the enjoyment of the puzzle. Some of us have stopped hitting our heads against the wall railing about it, but Matt hasn’t, and more power to him for that.
I don’t look at the easy clues but frankly not sure what they would be today.

@Matt

You are right, of course. The only people who would actually argue the other side are solvers who want to feel good about getting their gold stars on “late-week puzzles”, and the occasional contrarian.

For anyone who has recently spent much time in the archives from 10+ years ago, while also solving each puzzle du jour, the contrast is night and day; and the contrarian commentary that attempts to call that into question is really just gaslighting.

@Matt

I thought this was a Friday Across puzzle combined with a Monday-level Down. So… a Wednesday?

I agree that those Down clues took all the teeth out of this one. It’s great to have a way into such intimidating spanners, but I feel like I should have had to work a little harder for them.

@Matt, my question was basically the word "neutered". To me that implies perhaps you think the editors dumbed down the clues? 

In any case, I have no bones to pick with your assessment; I should have been more clear about what I didn't quite get. And of course, other than quoting stats, all of our comments are our subjective thoughts.

Thanks for the reply.

@Steve L, yep, I saw the stats. I get it! I've been solving for nearly 50 years, and yes, the puzzles have changed and evolved. The archives, I believe, go back to the beginning of Will Shortz's tenure. I remember being delighted when he significantly modernized and made the puzzle more accessible to solvers, especially compared to the Eugene Meleska era. 

That said, I did enjoy the difficulty of that era as well. I'm just a word nerd who had a question that I didn't think would be controversial! I didn't express my question well, and I realize that now.

I'm on vacation and I'm going to claim the sun has addled my brain.

@Susan E

I believe the editors have been enjoined to dumb down the clues and do so routinely later in the week.

And if they aren't doing this then they are failing miserably in their duty to smart them up, as it were.

@Kevin
It is a special kind of paranoia that sees an advertisement in every casual reference to a brand name.

Sometimes an Oreo is just an Oreo.

@Katie

Unless it’s a “Mountain: combining form,” which is how those four letters had to be clued before Shortz took over. 

Is that somehow better?

@Steve L
Huh?
3D is 5 letters, for one thing.

@Wyra

It means the base form of the extremely rare word “oreography,” which itself is a variant of “orography,” which is “the scientific study and physical description of mountains, mountain systems, and elevated terrain.”

Does that help?

@Barry Ancona

I don't know how or why, but I had heard of TUVALU at some point. I'm looking at the …VAL… sitting there in the puzzle and I  just started thinking, "that couldn't be TUVALU, could it?"

At least one of my kids was the right age for the Disney movie, so SCAR was a no-brainer.

@Teddy

On behalf of the complainers: we’re tired, boss.

(But yes, obviously this puzzle was entirely too damn easy for a Friday. Exhibit A: a handful of comments exactly like yours, such as the top-voted entry of the day.)

@Nancy
Re KATO
More scraggly than flowing locks in my recollection,  but that's the guy.

@Nancy
I thought you were a Cat Person?!
That was a nice gimme....  Charlotte the Kitty has long white "stockings" and adorable black "toe-beans"--as CrossWorld terms them--    Adorbs, of course.

@Barry Ancona 
@SP
Confirms my suspicion that forms of the S word is emu food.

